      "content": "A slow memory leak in your embedded project is like a sneaky goblin hiding in the shadows, waiting for the perfect moment to strike. To catch this goblin, you'll need to be as meticulous as a goblin tracker. Here's a systematic way to track down the leak:\n\n1. **Instrumentation**: Add some logging to your code, like placing traps for goblins. For instance, you can log the size of `log_store` at regular intervals or after each operation that modifies it. This will help you see when the size starts to grow unexpectedly.\n\n2. **Memory Allocation Tracking**: Since you're working with C++, you can use the `new` and `delete` operators to track allocations and deallocations. Wrap your `new` and `delete` calls with custom functions that log each allocation and deallocation. This way, you'll have a record of where memory is being allocated and freed, just like keeping a ledger of goblin sightings.\n\n3. **Code Review**: Sometimes, goblins hide in the most unexpected places. Review your code carefully, looking for any instances where memory might not be freed. Pay special attention to any conditional statements or loops that might be causing the leak.\n\n4. **Unit Testing**",
